    {
      "id": "tUROspwj2zU9rtWWwfEkb",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -596.0186315267414,
      "y": 375.99532588858756,
      "width": 700,
      "height": 300,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": "aE_QwboqjmTBBHE6_i6w4",
      "index": "a3",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 120815524,
      "version": 2370,
      "versionNonce": 171203422,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1774565266209,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "The data reveals a dynamic pattern in the number of tasks completed over time.\nStarting from early 2024, there is a noticeable fluctuation in task completion, with\nsignificant peaks and troughs. In the latter half of 2024, tasks completed generally\nincreased, peaking at **61,427** in May 2024. However, this was followed by a decline,\nreaching a low of **31,377** by late July 2024. \n\nThe trend reversed in the fall, with a notable rise in October 2024, reaching **58,045**.\nThis upward momentum continued into early 2025, with a peak of **64,261** in October\n2025. However, the beginning of 2026 shows a sharp decline, with tasks completed\ndropping to **8,744** by mid-February 2026. \n\nOverall, the data indicates a cyclical pattern with periods of growth followed by sharp\ndeclines. The most recent data suggests a significant downturn, highlighting potential\nchallenges in maintaining task completion rates. This pattern of fluctuation could be\nindicative of seasonal factors or operational changes impacting productivity.",
      "fontSize": 16,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "The data reveals a dynamic pattern in the number of tasks completed over time. Starting from early 2024, there is a noticeable fluctuation in task completion, with significant peaks and troughs. In the latter half of 2024, tasks completed generally increased, peaking at **61,427** in May 2024. However, this was followed by a decline, reaching a low of **31,377** by late July 2024. \n\nThe trend reversed in the fall, with a notable rise in October 2024, reaching **58,045**. This upward momentum continued into early 2025, with a peak of **64,261** in October 2025. However, the beginning of 2026 shows a sharp decline, with tasks completed dropping to **8,744** by mid-February 2026. \n\nOverall, the data indicates a cyclical pattern with periods of growth followed by sharp declines. The most recent data suggests a significant downturn, highlighting potential challenges in maintaining task completion rates. This pattern of fluctuation could be indicative of seasonal factors or operational changes impacting productivity.",
      "autoResize": false,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
